<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:302px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lombard_language_situation_map.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/08/Lombard_language_situation_map.svg/300px-Lombard_language_situation_map.svg.png" width="300" height="314" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lombard_language_situation_map.svg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="http://bits.wikimedia.org/skins-1.17/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Lombard in Europe</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Lombard</b> is a member of the <a href="/wiki/Cisalpine_(linguistics)" title="Cisalpine (linguistics)" class="mw-redirect">Cisalpine</a> or <a href="/wiki/Gallo-Italic" title="Gallo-Italic" class="mw-redirect">Gallo-Italic</a> group within the <a href="/wiki/Romance_languages" title="Romance languages">Romance languages</a>. It is spoken natively in Northern <a href="/wiki/Italy" title="Italy">Italy</a> (most of <a href="/wiki/Lombardy" title="Lombardy">Lombardy</a> and some areas of neighbouring regions, notably the eastern side of <a href="/wiki/Piedmont" title="Piedmont">Piedmont</a>) and Southern <a href="/wiki/Switzerland" title="Switzerland">Switzerland</a> (<a href="/wiki/Ticino" title="Ticino">Ticino</a> and <a href="/wiki/Graub%C3%BCnden" title="Graubünden">Graubünden</a>).</p>
<p>The two main varieties (<a href="/wiki/Western_Lombard_language" title="Western Lombard language" class="mw-redirect">Western Lombard language</a> and <a href="/wiki/Eastern_Lombard_language" title="Eastern Lombard language">Eastern Lombard language</a>) show differences and are often, but not always, mutually comprehensible<sup class="Template-Fact" title="This claim needs references to reliable sources from February 2011" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed">citation needed</a></i>]</sup>. The union of <a href="/wiki/Western_Lombard" title="Western Lombard" class="mw-redirect">Western Lombard or Insubric</a>, <a href="/wiki/Eastern_Lombard" title="Eastern Lombard" class="mw-redirect">Eastern Lombard</a> and intermediate varieties under the denomination of "Lombard" is a matter of debate, and it has been argued that the two might potentially form separate languages<sup class="Template-Fact" title="This claim needs references to reliable sources from February 2011" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed">citation needed</a></i>]</sup></p>
